A Software Stack for CXL Environments, presented by Steve Scargall (MemVerge)

Steve Scargall outlines MemVerge’s view of the **software stack for CXL**, with emphasis on **Linux** and **Type 3 (memory expansion)** devices, much of which also applies to Type 2 and future Type 1 work. At the bottom sit CXL hardware device classes from the specification; above them the **kernel** exposes capacity through **drivers** that are largely upstream today. Two common consumption models appear: **device DAX** (a character device “blob” of memory that applications manage with SDKs), versus switching the namespace to **system RAM**, which presents CXL memory as an extra **NUMA node** of DRAM without CPUs—suitable for **unmodified** NUMA-aware workloads. **Middleware** and **tiering** sit above: the kernel’s **AutoNUMA** and transparent page placement can migrate pages between **DRAM and CXL** (latency tiering); MemVerge adds products such as **Memory Machine** and is working toward **bandwidth** tiering and **n-level** tiering when memory spans local devices, switched paths, or **CXL 3.x** multi-hop fabrics with heterogeneous latency.

**Persistent CXL** (Samsung-style memory‑semantic SSDs with DRAM cache) reuses **Optane-era** drivers and can surface capacity via **DAX filesystem** semantics—mmap and file I/O at memory-like speeds. The talk traces **ndctl / CXL CLI / cxl** command-line evolution alongside **kernel** milestones and **CXL 1.1 → 3.x** spec features (noting that kernel work lands incrementally, not as a single spec dump). A “crib sheet” mentions **lstopo**, **lspci**, vendor fabric tools, **QEMU CXL “flight simulator”** for device expansion and **shared memory** between VMs, **DCD (dynamic capacity device)** bring-up, and **fabric management (FM)** as distributed, minimal-mandatory APIs for switches, hosts, and orchestration (including **Kubernetes** resource provisioning) rather than one monolithic stack. **Telemetry** and **RAS**—including **CXL PMU (CPMU)** ideas in **CXL 3.0**—are beginning to surface in **recent mainline** kernels with hardware-dependent support. The speaker closes with community pointers: **CXL Forum** going online, **Discord**, **CXL Academy**, **Linux CXL community**, **Linux Plumbers**, and **CMS** work under **OCP**.
